    Author            = 'Driver Automation Tool Contributors'
    Description       = 'Automates downloading, packaging, and distributing Dell and Lenovo drivers and BIOS updates for SCCM/ConfigMgr environments. 1.12.0 adds hardware-aware DriverUpdates installs: the Dell catalog''s per-driver PCI hardware IDs (VEN/DEV) are captured into manifest.json, and the apply script enumerates the device''s present PCI devices and skips any DUP whose target hardware is absent (conservative - DUPs that declare no hardware still run). This stops e.g. a Qualcomm NIC DUP from running on an Intel-NIC SKU and reduces the unneeded DUPs that get AV-quarantined. Adds a virtual-machine guard so AVD/VDI/Hyper-V/VMware hosts skip driver and BIOS installs entirely (apply-time guard plus a Model-not-Virtual requirement rule on new apps). Non-applicable DUPs whose .EXE was AV-quarantined no longer fail the deployment. 1.12.1 fixes the recurring "Could not set custom return codes ... Unable to find type [...ErrorClass]" failure: the SDK types (SccmSerializer/ErrorClass/CustomError) are now resolved by reflection off the loaded ConfigMgr assembly instead of PowerShell''s [typename] resolver, which never saw them on some console builds. This also restores the 1.11.5 deployment-type idempotency pre-check (it shared the same broken type reference and was silently falling back to "always update", re-introducing CI-revision churn), so vendor exit codes (Dell DUP 2/3/4/5/6, Lenovo 256) map correctly and apps stop churning revisions. 1.12.2 fixes the CMTrace log timestamp: the timezone bias was written as a hardcoded "+" followed by the raw UTC offset, so machines west of UTC logged "...+-300", which CMTrace couldn''t parse and showed a wrong/blank date-time on every line. Both loggers (Write-DATLog and the client apply script) now emit a correctly-signed bias. 1.12.3 fixes custom return codes still failing on 1.12.2 with "is loaded but does not expose expected type(s): ErrorClass, CustomError": those types live in a different SDK assembly than SccmSerializer on some console builds, and the 1.12.1/1.12.2 resolver only inspected a single DLL. The resolver now searches every loaded assembly per type and, if any are still missing, loads the whole ApplicationManagement* DLL family from the console bin directory before giving up. This also clears the companion "DT idempotency pre-check failed" line (same resolver), so no-op deployment-type updates stop bumping CI revisions. 1.12.4 finally fixes custom return codes on console builds where ErrorClass/CustomError cannot be located by name at all (1.12.3 force-loaded all ApplicationManagement* DLLs and still failed): the CustomError and ErrorClass types are now read directly off a live default return-code object on the deployment type (every script DT ships with default codes), so no by-name type lookup is needed. The serializer-only resolver no longer requires those two types, which also clears the "DT idempotency pre-check failed" line on these builds. 1.12.5 fixes the follow-on "Deployment type Installer has no CustomReturnCodes collection to update" error: a freshly-created script DT comes back with a null CustomReturnCodes (Add-CMScriptDeploymentType does not seed default codes), so there was nothing to sample. The CustomError and ErrorClass types are now read from the Installer''s CustomReturnCodes property-type metadata (always present, no live element or by-name lookup needed), and the collection is instantiated when null. 1.12.6 stops DriverUpdates Applications from forcing a restart after every run: the deployment type''s post-install behavior changes from ForceReboot to BasedOnExitCode for all modes, so a device only restarts when the install script returns 3010 (a Dell DUP/Flash64W 2/6, Lenovo SRSETUP 256, or pnputil 3010/259 that actually signaled reboot-required). A run where every DUP was skipped (hardware not present / already current) now exits 0 and does NOT reboot - fixing the "Success - no reboot required" run that still popped the restart countdown. With the deployment''s default RebootOutsideServiceWindow=$false, the genuine soft reboot is deferred to the collection''s maintenance window; re-syncing flips existing DriverUpdates apps to BasedOnExitCode in place. Also fixes the DATApply.log date/time in CMTrace: the trap and startup-marker lines were written as bare "[HH:mm:ss] ..." text in an otherwise CMTrace-formatted file, so CMTrace showed a wrong/blank date-time on those lines. All lines now share one CMTrace <![LOG[...]]> formatter, and timestamps render with InvariantCulture so a non-US client locale can''t corrupt the time separator. 1.13.0 adds an optional "Create / ensure maintenance window on collection" section to the Deploy Applications tab (and EnsureMaintenanceWindow / MWStart / MWDurationMinutes / MWRecurrence / MWDayOfWeek / MWName parameters on Invoke-DATDeployApplications). When enabled, a DAT-named maintenance window with a configurable start, duration, and None/Daily/Weekly recurrence is created or updated on the target collection before the apps are deployed, so a reboot the install script signals (exit 3010) is deferred to that window instead of firing right after install. The window is idempotent by name (updated in place if present, never duplicated, admin-created windows left untouched) and general (ApplyTo=Any), which also governs software updates and task sequences on the collection - the deploy confirmation warns before applying it to broad collections. 1.14.0 adds a standalone Scripts\Deploy-DATApplications.ps1 wrapper so the same bulk deployment (and the optional maintenance-window creation) can be driven from the command line, a scheduled task, or a runbook without the GUI. It forwards all Invoke-DATDeployApplications parameters - including EnsureMaintenanceWindow / MWStart / MWDurationMinutes / MWRecurrence / MWDayOfWeek / MWName - and returns an exit code for automation (0 = all deployments and the window succeeded, 1 = a deployment or the window failed, 2 = a fatal error). 1.15.0 stops an inapplicable graphics DUP from failing a DriverUpdates deployment. Dell ships every GPU option''s driver for a model and many graphics DUPs carry no PCIInfo, so on (for example) an AMD box the NVIDIA driver still ran and reported "no compatible hardware" as a generic exit 1 - failing the whole Application even though every driver the device needed had installed. The apply script now detects the GPU brands actually present (NVIDIA/AMD from display adapters and raw PCI, Intel from display adapters) and skips a graphics DUP for a brand that is not installed; if such a DUP still runs and errors, it is counted as not-applicable instead of a failure - unless that brand''s GPU IS present, in which case it is still surfaced as a real failure. The DriverUpdates summary gains a "skipped (GPU brand absent)" count. Re-sync to restage the updated apply script to clients. 1.15.1 caps the client DATApply.log size. The log already appended across runs (every write is Add-Content), but had no size limit; it now rolls over to a single .lo_ companion once it reaches MaxLogSizeMB (default 5 MB) and starts a fresh .log, keeping on-disk size to about 2x the cap while preserving recent history (CMTrace shows the .log/.lo_ pair together). Re-sync to restage the updated apply script. 2.0.0 reworks the admin GUI from WinForms to a modern WPF interface and raises the module to PowerShell 7.4+ (CompatiblePSEditions Core). Start-DATGui now hosts the window on a dedicated STA runspace so it launches correctly under pwsh (which defaults to MTA). The five tabs (Models, SCCM Settings, Progress, Package Management, Deploy Applications) and every existing operation are preserved one-to-one - only the presentation layer changed. The client-side apply scripts stay Windows PowerShell 5.1 compatible and are unaffected. This is the foundation for the first-class Intune deployment support (Win32 apps and native driver-update profiles) landing in subsequent 2.x releases. 2.1.0 fixes the WPF GUI event handlers - Connect, Refresh Models, and the other buttons reported a null window/controls reference because the handler scriptblocks did not retain Initialize-DATMainWindow local variables under the STA-runspace host. The shared controls map, window, cursors, and log list box now live in module scope, which the handler scriptblocks can see. Also adds light/dark theming that follows the Windows app setting (Set-DATWindowTheme reads AppsUseLightTheme and swaps the window DynamicResource brushes) and a responsive Grid/DockPanel layout with proportional star-sizing so the window scales cleanly with its size. 2.1.1 actually fixes the GUI event handlers - 2.1.0 moved the shared state to module scope, but WPF dispatches events re-entrantly on the STA runspace and that context does not resolve PowerShell variable scope (neither locals nor $script:) - only module functions resolve. Every handler and timer tick is now a closure (GetNewClosure) that bakes in the controls map, window, and cursors; mutable cross-handler state lives in one shared hashtable captured by those closures; and ConfigMgr connection state is read through the Get-DATCMState module function. Theme detection now reads AppsUseLightTheme via the .NET registry API so dark mode is detected reliably in the child runspace. 2.1.2 fixes the follow-on failure 2.1.1 introduced - GetNewClosure rebinds each handler to a throwaway module that cannot see this module own functions, so the closured handlers failed with Get-DATComboText / Show-DATWindowMessage not recognized. Handlers are now plain scriptblocks (so module functions resolve) and fetch their state through a Get-DATGui module function, since a module-function call is the only thing the WPF re-entrant event context resolves reliably. Settings load and auto-connect run in the window Loaded handler with the same pattern, so saved settings are restored again, and the theme is re-applied in Loaded. 2.1.3 fixes button clicks (2.1.2 restored settings load via the Loaded event, but clicks still failed with the helper functions not recognized). The Loaded event fires while the module call is still on the stack, so module functions resolve there; button clicks fire later from the WPF message pump - a re-entrant native callback that resolves commands only from the runspace global session state, where module-private functions are invisible. Start-DATGui now dot-sources the module into the GUI runspace global scope in addition to importing it, so every DAT function is reachable from the re-entrant event handlers. 2.1.3 launched nothing at all (silent failure): the global-scope load used . on the .psm1 path, but PowerShell only dot-sources .ps1 files and tried to run the .psm1 as an external program, so the module never loaded globally and Show-DATMainWindow was undefined. 2.1.4 loads the module body globally by building a scriptblock from the .psm1 text (seeding PSScriptRoot) and dot-sourcing that, which correctly defines every function in the GUI runspace global scope. Start-DATGui also now surfaces any GUI-runspace startup error to the host and to a DATGui-startup.log, so a launch failure is never silent again. The GUI state accessors (Set-DATGui / Get-DATGui) use $global:DATGui so handlers always read the object the window was wired with. 2.1.7 turns the per-DUP PCI hardware filter from enforcing to advisory. Field evidence on a Precision 3660 showed Dell''s catalog PCIInfo does not reliably enumerate every device ID a DUP actually supports (Intel UHD and I219 NIC DUPs were skipped despite the hardware being present), causing false-negative skips of drivers the device really needed. Each DUP whose catalog target hardware isn''t seen in the present-device enumeration now logs a "hardware advisory" warning and runs anyway, deferring the actual applicability call to the DUP''s own exit code (Dell 3/4/5 = not-applicable). The separate GPU-brand filter (NVIDIA/AMD/Intel) is unchanged - it uses vendor only and is still reliable. Re-sync to restage the updated apply script. 2.1.8 fixes Dell DUPs failing immediately with exit 1 in ~0.1s once the 2.1.7 advisory let them run on a Precision 3660. Dell DUPs extract their payload to the current working directory and fail instantly if it isn''t writable; under CCMExec/SYSTEM the apply script inherited a CWD of C:\Windows\System32 (the BIOS-flash code already set this explicitly - the DUP-loop missed it). The DUP-loop now passes WorkingDirectory = the package staging path. Each DUP''s stdout/stderr is also captured to %WINDIR%\Temp\DATDupLogs\<session>\<dup>.{stdout,stderr}.log so a future "exit N" failure is diagnosable from the file the DUP actually wrote, and the failure log line names both files. Also fixes a hardware-advisory false positive where a manifest entry with no HardwareIds was logging "catalog targets ()" - null/empty IDs are now filtered before the advisory engages. Re-sync to restage the updated apply script. 2.1.9 adds Dell-framework diagnostics after a field run where every DUP still exited 1 in ~0.1s with empty stdout/stderr (which is expected - DUPs are GUI apps that never write to the console). Every DUP now runs with Dell''s documented /l= switch so the framework writes a per-DUP .dup.log; on failure the apply log quotes that log''s last lines, or states explicitly that NO framework log was written - meaning the process was killed before Dell''s framework initialized, the signature of AV/EDR terminating installers spawned from the CM cache. When every failure in a run is instant (<2s), a Severity-3 diagnostic names the likely endpoint-security cause, where to look (AV console, C:\ProgramData\Dell\UpdatePackage\Log), and a manual elevated test command to discriminate. Re-sync to restage the updated apply script. 2.1.10 fixes the cause the 2.1.9 framework logs surfaced on the 3660: every DUP wrote "Error locating default extractpath" - Dell''s framework couldn''t find a usable %TEMP% to unpack its payload into. (This also confirms AV/EDR is NOT killing the DUPs - Dell''s framework was running fine.) The apply script now creates a per-DUP extract directory under %WINDIR%\Temp\DATDupExtract\<session>\dup-<index>\ and overrides TMP/TEMP for the child process so Dell''s GetTempPath() lands on a guaranteed-writable path; the original TMP/TEMP are restored after each DUP via try/finally. Stdout/stderr capture is dropped (DUPs are GUI apps; the 2.1.9 captures were all empty as expected), and the all-instant-failures Severity-3 diagnostic now branches on whether Dell framework logs were written - "Error locating default extractpath" is now called out by name as the signature for the TMP issue this build addresses, while the no-log path still flags the AV/EDR pattern. Re-sync to restage the updated apply script. 2.2.0 adds a Dell Command Update engine for DriverUpdates packages. Sync now writes a DCU-compatible repository catalog (DCUCatalog.xml, cloned from the per-model catalog''s own SoftwareComponent nodes) into every Dell DriverUpdates package alongside the staged DUPs - including backfilling fingerprint-current packages on their next refresh. At apply time, Dell devices with dcu-cli.exe installed hand the whole install to DCU against that local repository: DCU inventories the actual device (real PnP IDs and installed versions) so applicability is Dell''s own logic instead of catalog PCIInfo guesswork, DUP children run under the Dell-signed DCU service (the execution context security tooling already trusts), and DCU manages its own extraction. The machine''s existing DCU settings are exported first and restored after the run, so a tech''s Dell-cloud catalogLocation config is never hijacked. Exit mapping: dcu-cli 0/500 report success, 1/5 signal reboot via the existing 3010 path, anything else fails the deployment with the dcu output log''s last lines quoted into DATApply.log. Devices without DCU, non-Dell devices, and pre-2.2.0 packages fall back to the built-in DUP engine automatically - no new settings or parameters. Re-sync to restage the apply script and emit the catalog. 2.2.1 diagnoses the field exit-107 from dcu-cli: BOTH /configure calls (settings export and catalogLocation) failed identically before the catalog was ever read, pointing at the invocation, not the catalog. dcu-cli is a console app, so every call now captures stdout/stderr per-command and quotes the console tail into DATApply.log on failure (dcu-cli prints its validation errors in plain text - the next run names the real cause). Adds a version gate (DCU 3.x has a different CLI grammar; engine now requires 4.0+ and logs the detected dcu-cli version) and a single-instance pre-flight: if a DCU scan/GUI is already running (dcu-cli is single-instance), waits up to 2 minutes, then falls back to the built-in engine for that run instead of failing. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.2.2 fixes the exit-107 root cause the 2.2.1 console capture named: DCU 5.x rejects path options inside "reserved folders", and the session dir lived in C:\Windows\Temp. The DCU session (settings backup, localized catalog, logs) moves to %ProgramData%\DriverAutomationTool\DCU\<session>, and because ccmcache is also under C:\Windows, the staged DUPs are hardlinked (zero-copy, same volume; copy fallback) into a session repo under ProgramData and baseLocation points there - originals in ccmcache untouched, links removed after the run. The built-in engine''s per-DUP TMP/extract root also moves from C:\Windows\Temp to %ProgramData%\DriverAutomationTool\DupExtract (Dell''s own DUP default extract family). DUP framework-log quoting now strips per-line timestamps and the fixed footer (Name of Exit Code/Result/Execution terminated/######) that was burying the actual error line, so failure lines quote the real reason. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.2.3 moves the client working root again after the 2.2.2 run proved DCU 5.6 treats ProgramData as a reserved folder too (same exit-107 path-validation error on -exportSettings/-catalogLocation under C:\ProgramData; the hardlinked repo staged fine and was never the problem - DCU rejected the paths before reading any file). The DCU session (catalog, settings backup, repo, logs) and the built-in engine''s per-DUP TMP/extract root now live under C:\Temp\DriverAutomationTool\ - the path family Dell''s own dcu-cli documentation uses and the remaining non-reserved candidate; the now-footer-filtered DUP failure lines confirmed the framework still errors with "Error locating default extractpath" from ProgramData, consistent with the same reserved-path lineage. Both roots self-prune sessions older than 7 days since C:\Temp has no automatic cleanup. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.2.4 addresses the next exit-107 dcu-cli console error the 2.2.3 capture surfaced: "The path provided for option ''cataloglocation'' specifies an incorrect file type". DCU 5.x (5.6.0.17 in the field) now requires a .cab for -catalogLocation, not raw XML - so the apply script wraps the localized catalog in a CAB using the built-in Windows makecab.exe before pointing dcu-cli at it. The catalog itself also gets the xmlns="openmanifest" default namespace Dell''s schema requires (the cloned <SoftwareComponent> nodes inherit it without prefix). The localized XML is named CatalogPC.xml inside the CAB - Dell''s standard internal name. Path validation on -exportSettings, -catalogLocation, and the settings backup is now confirmed past on C:\Temp (the export/restore cycle worked end-to-end in 2.2.3), and no AV/Defender path-reputation issues were flagged on C:\Temp content in the field run. Re-sync to restage the apply script (the catalog also changes, so an unchanged driver set will see one DP refresh after import). 2.2.5 hardens the engine against the DCU self-update collision the first successful field run hit (configure + applyUpdates succeeded on the custom CAB catalog, then DCU updated itself 5.6->5.7 mid-run): the settings restore now retries up to 3 times 30s apart when DCU holds the config lock (exit 3004 "currently performing a self update"); a pristine settings copy is kept at the work root and is never overwritten by an export whose catalogLocation already points at a session catalog (so a failed restore can''t launder the hijacked config into the "original" on the next run - restore prefers pristine); dcu-cli exit 5 ("a previous operation requires a system reboot") at export/configure/restore now signals RebootRequired so the deployment ends 3010 and DCU works again after the restart; and the restore step only runs when this run actually changed the configuration. Every run''s DCU evidence (which catalog was used, what was applied) is in C:\Temp\DriverAutomationTool\DCU\<session>\: dcu-apply.log, applyUpdates.out.log, dcu-configure.log, plus DCU''s own C:\ProgramData\Dell\UpdateService\Log\Service.log. 2.2.6 makes the DCU engine FAIL CLOSED after the field smoking gun: DCU 5.6 rejected the custom catalog (SYSTEM_SECURITY_ERROR / "failed to provide any result") and then silently sourced 12 updates (1.1 GB) from Dell''s CLOUD catalog - including a BIOS flash, TPM firmware, and SupportAssist - none of it curated. The engine now runs a read-only /scan gate before any install: if the scan log shows the rejection markers, or the scan report proposes even one update whose file isn''t among the package''s staged DUPs (allowlist from manifest.json), or the report is missing/unparseable, NOTHING installs via DCU and the run falls back to the built-in DUP engine (still curated content, never Dell''s cloud). After /applyUpdates, the apply log is re-checked for the same markers and unverified provenance is reported as FAILURE rather than silent success. Configure now first attempts the raw XML catalog with -allowXML=enable (dcu-cli''s sanctioned path for plain XML catalogs, which may clear the security rejection), automatically falling back to the CAB configure when the option or file type is refused. 2.2.7 fixes the scan gate''s report matching after its first field firing: -allowXML was ACCEPTED (configure passed, no SYSTEM_SECURITY_ERROR), but the gate then flagged all 14 proposed updates as foreign with "unnamed (no file attr)" - the report''s update nodes don''t carry the guessed file/name attributes, so the verdict was unproven (could equally have been our own 14 applicable drivers). Matching is now content-based (a node is ours if its raw XML mentions a staged DUP filename, or secondarily its Dell package-ID token, e.g. 34HGT/P766C), the gate message no longer claims cloud-consult as fact, and a tripped gate dumps the update nodes'' attribute names plus sample raw XML into DATApply.log so the report schema self-documents for the next iteration. Fail-closed behavior is unchanged: no verified match, no DCU install, built-in engine runs the curated DUPs. 2.3.0 adds a configurable driver-exclusion list so known-problem DUPs never reach clients at all. New -ExcludeDrivers parameter on Invoke-DATSync (also config-file options.excludeDrivers and a "Driver exclusions" field on the Models tab Options group, persisted with settings): semicolon-separated name/filename patterns, wildcards supported, plain text matches as a substring (e.g. "Realtek Card Reader"). Exclusions are applied inside Get-DellIndividualDrivers - at the catalog-match level - so the overlay fingerprint, staged DUPs, manifest.json allowlist, and the DCU repository catalog all agree and an excluded driver cannot reach a device through either engine. Field driver for the feature: the Realtek Card Reader DUP ships a driver version on Microsoft''s vulnerable-driver blocklist, so every install attempt tripped the Defender ASR rule "Block abuse of in-the-wild exploited vulnerable signed drivers" and paged the security team; excluding it at sync stops the alerts at the source. Each exclusion is logged at sync ("Admin exclusion: ... matched pattern ...") and counted in the catalog-scan summary (admin-excluded). Note: adding or removing an exclusion intentionally changes the package fingerprint, so affected models rebuild once on the next sync. 2.4.0 adds proactive vulnerable-driver detection on both ends. Sync side: every DriverUpdates DUP is screened against the Microsoft Vulnerable Driver Blocklist (the list Defender''s ASR "Block abuse of in-the-wild exploited vulnerable signed drivers" rule enforces; downloaded from aka.ms/VulnerableDriverBlockList and cached 7 days with stale fallback) by extracting the DUP payload (/s /e=, no install) and matching each .sys''s name+FileVersion against the policy''s filename rules - matches log a Severity-3 warning naming the exact Driver-exclusion to add, plus an end-of-sync VULNERABLE-DRIVER SUMMARY. Verdicts are cached per DUP (filename+MD5) and invalidated when Microsoft ships a new blocklist version, so steady-state syncs re-screen nothing; screening is advisory (the DUP still ships until excluded) and is controlled by -ScreenVulnerableDrivers / options.screenVulnerableDrivers (default on). New public cmdlet Test-DATVulnerableDrivers screens any existing package folder on demand without a re-sync. Apply side: after every DUP run (success or failure - a DUP can exit 0 while Defender silently blocked its driver write), the client checks the Defender Operational log for ASR/quarantine events (1121/1117) in that DUP''s exclusive run window; the vulnerable-driver rule GUID is recognized specifically and DATApply.log names the exact exclusion to add, with a VULNERABLE-DRIVER ADVICE summary and a Defender-flag count in the run summary. Hash-only blocklist entries are not evaluated by sync screening (filename+version rules cover the practical majority, including the field Realtek card-reader case); the apply-side correlator is the net for those. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.4.1 closes the DCU scan gate''s last gap, established by the field schema dump: the custom catalog IS consumed (8 of 12 proposed updates carried our flat staged filenames), but DCU layers its own Dell system-update channel on top regardless of catalogLocation (field items: TPM 2.0 Firmware Update Utility, the DCU 5.7 self-update, plus BIOS/SupportAssist - their <file> entries carry Dell cloud FOLDER paths, not our filenames). The report parser now reads the real child-element schema (<release>/<name>/<type>/<file>), classifies ours-vs-foreign primarily by <file> basename against the manifest allowlist, and when foreign items appear it computes a per-run -updateType fence: if the foreign types (firmware/application/bios) are disjoint from our proposed types (driver), it re-scans with -updateType=<ourTypes>, re-verifies zero foreign, and applies with the same filter so applyUpdates'' internal re-scan cannot re-admit them. Overlapping or unmappable types keep the gate closed and fall back to the built-in engine - still nothing uncurated installs, ever. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.4.2 lands the field-identified root cause of the cloud merge: DCU''s "Default Source Location (dell.com)" setting blends dell.com content into custom-catalog scans and lets resident DCU run cloud passes on its own schedule (field: a post-self-update 3:13 PM autonomous DCU run applied BIOS/TPM/cloud drivers an hour after our gated run finished cleanly). The engine now disables it for the duration of the run via /configure -defaultSourceLocation=disable (graceful fallback on builds without the option, same pattern as -allowXML), with the settings restore returning the box to exactly its prior state. Settings-restore retries are now self-update-aware: exit 3004 ("currently performing a self update") retries every 60s for up to ~6 minutes (a self-update outlasted the old 2x30s window), other failures keep short retries, reboot-pending (5) still doesn''t retry. Recommendation recorded here for ops: with this tool as the update channel, set DCU fleet-wide via policy to unchecked Default Source Location and no automatic update schedule, so resident DCU cannot self-deploy cloud content between tool runs. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.5.0 makes that recommendation a first-class feature: a new public cmdlet Set-DATDellCommandUpdateMode and a module-free single-file Scripts\Set-DATDcuManaged.ps1 (SCCM Scripts / Intune / scheduled task ready) configure DCU on the local machine to passive mode in one shot - defaultSourceLocation=disable, scheduleAuto=disable, scheduleAction=DoNothing, updatesNotification=disable, userConsent=disable, systemRestartDeferral=enable, installationDeferral=enable, autoSuspendBitLocker=disable - so DCU never auto-scans, auto-installs, or pulls from Dell''s cloud catalog and only acts when the apply-side DCU engine drives it. Sets a registry marker (HKLM\SOFTWARE\MSEndpointMgr\DriverAutomation\DcuManagedMode = DATManaged) the engine reads on every run to RE-ASSERT the managed settings defensively (idempotent), so a DCU self-update or a GPO refresh that flipped values back is corrected before the next install. Per-key graceful fallback (the same -allowXML pattern) - a build that doesn''t support one option logs a warning and continues with the others. Mode Default reverts to Dell out-of-box behavior. 2.6.0 makes DAT-managed mode DEFAULT-ON in the DriverUpdates application itself: every Dell device the apply script runs on gets DCU locked to passive (no dell.com source, no scheduled scans, no auto-downloads/installs) before the settings snapshot, so the post-run restore lands back in managed state - no separate deployment of the cmdlet/standalone script needed. The registry marker becomes the opt-out: Set-DATDellCommandUpdateMode -Mode Default (or the standalone script -Mode Default) marks a device DcuManagedMode=Default and the engine then leaves that device''s DCU autonomy settings alone (per-run scan purity still applies). The engine writes DcuManagedMode=DATManaged after each assertion for inventory visibility. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.6.1 fixes the two gaps the first 2.6.0 field run exposed (DP82132: "2 applied, 6 not supported" and the settings restore re-enabling dell.com). Lockdown option names corrected for the real dcu-cli grammar: scheduleManual=enable is the no-schedule knob (scheduleAuto=disable was wrong), scheduleAction only accepts NotifyAvailableUpdates/DownloadAndNotify/DownloadInstallAndNotify (DoNothing was invalid; the least-action value is set as belt and braces), and failed keys are now NAMED in the log so each build''s unsupported options are visible. The managed sequence is now asserted TWICE per run - pre-run (so the pristine snapshot trends managed) and post-restore (so the box always ENDS locked down even when the restore loaded a pristine captured before managed mode existed, which is exactly how the field box got dell.com re-enabled). The restore''s job is un-hijacking catalogLocation, never undoing the lockdown. Cmdlet and standalone script sequences updated to match. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.6.2 adds scan-exit-500 diagnostics. Field question on DP82132: a 3630 with an installed Intel UHD Graphics driver 31.0.101.2135 had a newer 31.0.101.2140 DUP in its package, yet DCU returned "no applicable updates" - is DCU genuinely evaluating our catalog or short-circuiting? The exit-500 path was previously silent. It now dumps a manifest summary (first 5 drivers + count), the scan report''s <Update> node count, the dcu-cli console tail and the dcu-scan.log tail, and a pointer to the localized CatalogPC.xml so a sample <SoftwareComponent> can be inspected. The next run''s log either vindicates DCU''s verdict (per-component reasoning recorded) or proves the catalog isn''t being evaluated as expected. No behavior change - purely additive logging. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.6.3 ends script-version ambiguity: the apply script now logs its own revision (ScriptRev = first 8 of its SHA-256) in the [START] and "DATApply starting" lines, and Copy-DATApplyScript logs the same rev when staging/skipping ("Staged Invoke-DATApply.ps1 (rev xxxxxxxx)") - matching client rev to sync rev settles "which script actually ran" in one glance. Field driver: a client executed a pre-sync local copy (2.6.0 behavior) minutes after the sync staged 2.6.1 to the share, and both sides looked current. Also resolves the new sync WARN "Installer type ScriptInstaller exposes no CustomReturnCodes property": DriverUpdates apps skip custom return codes entirely (their apply script normalizes every outcome to 0/1/3010, which SCCM maps natively), and the BIOS path now probes CustomReturnCodes/ReturnCodes/ExitCodes and, failing all three, names the code-related properties the Installer type actually exposes so the real property name surfaces in the log. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.6.4 lands three fixes from the first rev-stamped field run (DP82132, Rev=065a9bcd). (1) Crash fixed: the 2.6.2 exit-500 diagnostics invoked $ParseScanReport before its definition, crashing the "no applicable updates" path with "expression after ''&'' ... not valid" and marking the run Failed; the parser helpers now precede the scan, so the diagnostics complete. (2) The dell.com-revert root cause, proven by the named-key results: DCU rejects -defaultSourceLocation=disable whenever NO custom catalog is configured (exit 107) - so the pre-catalog assertion and every post-pristine-restore attempt failed, while the post-catalogLocation per-run call succeeded. Managed devices therefore no longer import pristine settings at end of run; instead the engine leaves resident DCU pointed at a PERSISTENT copy of the package catalog (work root, refreshed each run) and THEN disables dell.com - valid and durable, and the DCU GUI''s CHECK scans the curated set. Pristine restore remains for opted-out devices only. (3) Managed sequence trimmed to the field-proven set: scheduleManual as a bare flag (=enable drew 107), scheduleAction=NotifyAvailableUpdates (applied - even a stray schedule can only notify), updatesNotification=disable, autoSuspendBitLocker=disable; userConsent (106) and the deferral pair (109) dropped as build-dependent and redundant. Cmdlet and standalone script updated to match. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.7.0 fixes why scans against the package catalog found nothing while devices were genuinely behind: DCU''s scan inventories the system FIRST, using an Inventory Collector (invcol) it downloads FROM ITS CATALOG SOURCE - Dell''s catalogs carry an <InventoryComponent> entry for it, ours didn''t, and with dell.com now properly disabled DCU had no fallback, logging "Unable to retrieve system inventory information" and returning a meaningless exit-500 (field: DP82132 reported "everything current" with Last Update 7/28/2025 and a newer UHD driver sitting in the package). Sync now clones the <InventoryComponent> from Dell''s per-model catalog (master CatalogPC fallback), downloads invcol into the package, and embeds the reference in DCUCatalog.xml - scans run fully offline. The apply engine treats "Unable to retrieve system inventory" as scan-verdict-unusable and falls back to the built-in DUP engine instead of reporting a false Success, which protects every pre-2.7.0 package immediately. The persistent end state now also maintains DCU-persistent\repo (hardlinked payloads + collector, rebuilt each run, immune to session pruning) and rewrites the persistent catalog''s baseLocation to it, so resident DCU''s GUI CHECK and any between-run scans work entirely from the curated local set. Re-sync so packages gain the Inventory Collector and the updated catalog. 2.7.1 hardens the collector embed after a field sync errored and left the package without it (manifest unchanged, 35 EXEs, client correctly fell back): both sync call sites now wrap the embed in try/catch (an embed failure logs Severity 3 and the sync continues - it can never break a sync again), Get-DellInventoryComponent reports per-source findings (each catalog''s root element and InventoryComponent count, or the per-source error) so the sync log itself proves where the collector reference exists, and the node lookup switched to namespace-agnostic XPath with GetAttribute access. Also fixes a false alarm introduced by 2.6.4: the settings-hijack check matched the whole work root, flagging the legitimate persistent catalog (DCU-persistent\) as a hijack on every managed run - it now matches session directories (DCU\<timestamp>\) only. 2.7.2 escalates the two collector-embed warnings ("No usable <InventoryComponent> found ... Sources inspected: ..." and "Could not download the Inventory Collector") from Severity 2 to Severity 3: a field sync completed green while silently shipping a catalog without the collector because the only trace was an easy-to-miss [WARN] - a condition that disables DCU scanning fleet-wide deserves red. 2.8.0 finally addresses the built-in engine''s "Error locating default extractpath" plague (DP33667 until a DCU reinstall cured it; DP82132''s 2019-2021-era DUPs): Dell DUP frameworks resolve a DEFAULT extract path independent of TMP/TEMP and the working directory - legacy DUPs default to C:\dell\drivers, DCH-era DUPs to C:\ProgramData\Dell\Drivers - and die instantly when that root can''t be created. Two layers: the engine now pre-creates and write-probes both roots before the DUP loop (logging any root that stays unwritable), and when a DUP still exits 1 with the extractpath signature in its framework log, a per-DUP fallback re-runs it with the documented /s /e= extract-only switch (which bypasses default-path resolution because WE name the destination) and installs any INF-based payload via the existing pnputil machinery (Install-InfTree, including its reboot signaling and lenient batch policy). Fallback success rewrites the DUP''s exit code to 0 so markers/counters/summary flow unchanged; firmware/app payloads without INFs keep the original failure with a clear note. Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.8.1 closes the collector-embed visibility gap and the repo-staging filter bug a field sync log exposed: the embed''s FOUND path and already-staged path were completely silent (the only log evidence was a second "Found 2 unique catalog(s)" line), so a successful prior embed was indistinguishable from a failed one - both now log explicitly ("InventoryComponent found: <file>" / "Inventory Collector already staged in package"). And the client repo staging (session repo + persistent repo) hardlinked *.exe only, so a collector shipped with any other extension (.cab is common for Dell inventory components) was present in the package but absent from the repo DCU reads - the catalog referenced it, DCU couldn''t fetch it from baseLocation, and every scan failed inventory despite a correctly-built package. Both repos now stage ALL payload files (everything except manifest.json, DCUCatalog.xml, and *.ps1). Re-sync to restage the apply script, then re-copy any manual test folders. 2.8.2 adds a content-completeness check at apply time: every file the DCU catalog references (SoftwareComponents and the InventoryComponent) is verified present in the content, and missing files are named with a clear "your copy is incomplete or stale - re-copy the entire share / let the content refresh finish" warning. Field driver: a manual test folder was refreshed with the new apply script but not the newly-staged InvColPC_*.exe, so inventory kept failing while the share had been complete for days (the 2.8.1 found/already-staged logging proved it: "InventoryComponent found: InvColPC_13.8.0.155.exe" / "Inventory Collector already staged in package"). Also field-confirmed this round: the extractpath root cause is an ACL lockdown - C:\ProgramData\Dell\Drivers denied write access even to SYSTEM (the 2.8.0 probe named it), which is why every DCH-era DUP died instantly for weeks; C:\dell\drivers was created successfully and the extract+pnputil fallback was observed working end-to-end (8 INFs, pnputil exit 0). 2.9.0 merges the GUI redesign into the DCU-era code line (presentation only - the sync/deploy back end and the client apply scripts are untouched): the five tabs become a left sidebar navigation rail (Models, Package Management, Deploy Applications, Progress, SCCM Settings - a templated TabControl whose handlers switch to the Progress tab by name, so the order is flexible); the palette is dark-mode-first with a System/Dark/Light theme picker in the header (persisted with Save Settings) and detection that reads both AppsUseLightTheme and SystemUsesLightTheme via OpenSubKey and goes dark if either is dark, fixing the window that came up light on a dark desktop; combo boxes get a themed template so their text is readable in dark mode; grid selection checkboxes become full-cell single-click DataGridTemplateColumns (no more dead-centre-only, click-twice toggling); Refresh Models runs the Dell/Lenovo/Surface catalog fetch on a background runspace inside the imported module session state (the model-list functions are module-private) with a progress bar, so the window no longer freezes and a fetch failure is surfaced instead of a silent zero; toolbar buttons and labels were resized so nothing clips. The 2.3.0 driver-exclusions input is preserved in the redesigned Options panel. 2.9.1 fixes Package Management (Remove Selected and Apply Action) and Deploy Selected failing with an empty PackageID / a stuck "1 package" count: those three handlers wrapped Get-DATGridSelectedRows in @(...), which boxed the returned List as a single array element, so $SelectedRows[0] was the List rather than a DataRow - the row count read as 1 regardless of selection and PackageID/Name came through empty. They now consume the List directly. The model and DP/DPG selection paths already consumed it directly and were unaffected; Get-DATGridSelectedRows gained a note warning against the @() wrap. 2.9.2 removes the System option from the header Theme picker - its detection could not reliably follow a desktop whose Windows mode and app mode differ - leaving a plain Dark / Light toggle that defaults to Dark; a previously saved System preference loads as Dark. 2.10.0 begins first-class Intune delivery (both Win32 LOB apps and native Windows driver-update profiles) on top of the existing read-only Graph slice. This build adds the in-module .intunewin packaging engine: New-DATIntuneWinPackage zips a staged content folder, encrypts it into Microsoft''s Win32 payload layout (AES-256-CBC plus an HMAC-SHA256 over IV+ciphertext, with the SHA-256 file digest), and writes Detection.xml - producing a portable .intunewin with no IntuneWinAppUtil.exe dependency, and Get-DATIntuneWinContent reads one back for upload. The packaging is round-trip verified by unit tests (HMAC, decrypt, digest, and source-file recovery). Graph publishing, assignment, and the GUI surface land in subsequent 2.10.x builds. 2.10.1 adds the Win32 publish path and a public New-DATIntuneWin32App cmdlet: it packages a staged folder, then runs the full Graph beta sequence (create win32LobApp, content version, content file, wait for the Azure Storage SAS, block-blob upload the encrypted payload with mid-transfer SAS renewal, commit with the fileEncryptionInfo, and point the app at the committed content version), then optionally assigns it to Entra groups (include/exclude, required/available/uninstall). The install command and detection reuse the SCCM builders (Get-DATInstallCommand and Get-DATDetectionScript), so an Intune device runs the identical Invoke-DATApply with the identical HKLM:\SOFTWARE\MSEndpointMgr\DriverAutomation registry-marker detection. The body construction, blob chunking, publish sequence, and assignment targets are covered by mocked unit tests. The GUI surface and native Windows driver-update profiles follow. 2.10.2 hardens the Intune connection for the app-only model an Entra admin authorizes: Connect-DATIntune now supports certificate-based client credentials (a signed RS256 JWT assertion via -CertificateThumbprint or -ClientCertificate) alongside the client secret, because many tenants disable secrets by policy; token refresh re-signs the assertion. Adds the DeviceManagementConfiguration.ReadWrite.All scope needed for driver-update profiles, a Get-DATIntuneRequiredPermission cmdlet as the single source of truth for the permissions to grant, and a docs/Intune-Setup.md app-registration guide (permissions, admin consent, certificate vs secret, and how to connect). The certificate assertion is unit-tested end-to-end (claims plus signature verification). 2.10.3 adds the second Intune delivery model - native Windows driver-update profiles (deviceManagement/windowsDriverUpdateProfiles), which govern the drivers Microsoft publishes through Windows Update for assigned devices. New cmdlets: New-DATIntuneDriverUpdateProfile (manual approval, or automatic with a 0-30 day deferral, plus optional group assignment), Get-DATIntuneDriverUpdateProfile (list/get), Get-DATIntuneDriverInventory (a profile''s drivers, filterable by approval status), and Set-DATIntuneDriverApproval (Approve/Decline/Suspend inventory drivers via the profile executeAction). Get-DATIntuneRequiredPermission is now exported for setup/diagnostics. Profile body construction, assignment targets, inventory filtering, and the approval action are unit-tested. The GUI surface for both delivery models follows. 2.11.0 adds the Intune tab to the GUI so both delivery models are usable from the interface: an app-only connection panel (certificate thumbprint or client secret, Test, Disconnect, and a Required-permissions readout from Get-DATIntuneRequiredPermission), an Entra group search shared by both actions, Publish Driver Package as a Win32 app (the slow package-and-upload runs on a background runspace that adopts the live token via Export-/Import-DATIntuneSession and streams to the Progress tab), and Create Windows Driver-Update Profile (manual, or automatic with a deferral). Also corrects two just-added details: the driver approval action sends the lowercase Graph enum (approve/decline/suspend), and the carried-over client secret is decoded with PtrToStringBSTR for cross-platform correctness. 2.11.1 cross-checks the entire Intune write path against the Microsoft Graph beta documentation and confirms it correct: the win32LobApp body (minimumSupportedOperatingSystem and detectionRules both valid), the content create/renewUpload/commit flow and its uploadState values, the fileEncryptionInfo, the mobileApp and windowsDriverUpdateProfile assign shapes, the profile create (approvalType manual/automatic), and the driver executeAction (actionName approve/decline/suspend). The only adjustments were spec-exactness @odata.type tags added to the commit fileEncryptionInfo and to each win32LobApp return code to match the documented examples. 2.12.0 syncs the Surface model catalog in OEMSources.json against Microsoft''s official driver/firmware table (learn.microsoft.com/surface/manage-surface-driver-and-firmware-updates), growing it from 31 to 54 models. Surface has no machine-readable catalog (the model-to-Download-Center-ID map is maintained by hand), so the list had drifted out of date. Added: the 2025 devices - Surface Pro 12th Edition Intel (108671) and Snapdragon (108706), the actual flagship "Surface Pro 12" that succeeds the Pro 11, plus the separate smaller Surface Pro 12-inch 1st Edition (108199), Surface Laptop 13-inch Snapdragon (108198) / Intel (108670), and Surface Laptop 8th Edition Intel (108669) / Snapdragon (108705); the Intel siblings Microsoft now splits out (Surface Pro 11 Intel 108013, Surface Laptop 7 Intel 108014); and other catalogued models (Surface Pro 10 with 5G 106292, Surface Laptop 7 5G for Business 108347, Surface Studio 2+ 104681, and the Surface Book / Go / Studio / Surface 3 back-catalog). Fixed a broken entry: "Surface Pro 9 with 5G" pointed at 104678, which is actually a Windows Group Policy reference spreadsheet rather than a driver pack - corrected to the real SQ3 5G pack 105941. Surface Hub (ships an OS image, not a driver MSI) and Surface Docks (accessories) are intentionally excluded. All packs use the standard Product_Win<release>_<build>_<version>.msi naming the Download Center scraper already parses. 2.13.0 adds a new sync type "BIOS Updates (DCU)" that installs the latest Dell BIOS through the same Dell Command Update engine the DriverUpdates path uses, instead of Flash64W - reusing the fail-closed scan gate (custom-catalog-only, allowlisted to the staged BIOS DUP) and the same DCU lockdown/persistent-catalog end state. The sync builds a single-BIOS package per model (latest at sync time): the BIOS DUP, a manifest.json with one entry, a DCUCatalog.xml carrying the BIOS''s catalog SoftwareComponent plus the embedded Inventory Collector for offline scans, and Flash64W.exe staged alongside as a guaranteed fallback. Get-DellBIOSUpdate now also returns the BIOS''s ComponentXml so the catalog can describe it the way DCU expects. New parameter -IncludeBIOSDCU on Invoke-DATSync (and options.includeBIOSDCU in config) and a "BIOS Updates (DCU)" entry in the GUI Package Type dropdown; Dell-only and Application-mode-only (the GUI''s deployment-platform gate still applies). At apply time the new Mode "BIOSDCU" runs the existing pre-flash version skip and BitLocker suspend, then hands the install to the DCU engine; when DCU is unavailable or its scan gate rejects the run, the client falls back to Invoke-DellBIOSFlash so a device without DCU still gets its BIOS through the proven Flash64W path. SCCM owns the reboot via -reboot=disable + the existing BasedOnExitCode mapping, and the BIOS password (-BIOSPassword) passes through to either engine the same way. Application name prefix "BIOS Update (DCU) - ..." keeps these packages distinct from the legacy "BIOS Update - ..." flow, which is preserved as-is. Re-sync to start producing BIOSDCU packages. 2.13.1 closes a silent fleet-wide trap in BIOS deployments: detection for BIOS / BIOSDCU Applications was registry-marker-only, so anything that wrote Status=Installed without the firmware actually moving - a flash whose mandatory reboot was deferred indefinitely, a Flash64W exit 3/4/5 (not applicable to this SKU/revision) that was being mapped to plain Installed, or a null exit treated as soft-reboot success - left the marker saying Installed forever and SCCM short-circuited on it, so the deployment never re-ran and entire fleets sat at old BIOS levels with no visible failure. Detection is now HARDWARE-AWARE: the script reads Win32_BIOS.SMBIOSBIOSVersion live and reports installed only when the device''s actual firmware is at or above the target (with the apply script''s same exact / [System.Version] / first-numeric-dotted fallback comparison). The apply script now also records the live BIOS string at marker-write time as BIOSAtMarker, and writes a distinct NotApplicable status for Flash64W 3/4/5 instead of the old Installed lie. When versions can''t be compared numerically (some non-numeric vendor tags), or when the vendor utility reported NotApplicable, detection falls back to the marker - but only when the BIOSAtMarker anchor exactly equals the device''s current live BIOS, so any firmware change re-arms hardware-based detection automatically. Driver and DriverUpdates detection stay marker-based (no single hardware version exists to verify). Re-sync to restage the apply script and refresh existing apps - on the next maintenance window every device that was falsely "installed" but is actually behind on BIOS will go non-compliant and re-flash, surfacing the at-risk fleet through the deployment''s native compliance view without a separate report. 2.13.2 fixes BIOSDCU silently exiting clean when DCU''s scan returned "no applicable updates" while the device was genuinely behind on BIOS. Field firing: a Latitude/OptiPlex on BIOS 1.8.1 with the staged BIOSDCU app targeting 1.9.0 - the pre-flash check confirmed the device was behind, the DCU engine ran, and its scan returned exit-500 "everything current" anyway (DCU''s applicability rules - SystemID match, dellVersion parsing, Inventory Collector verdict, SupportedDevices PCI - disagreed with the catalog). Install-BIOSDCU treated the 0 return as success and exited without flashing, so the BIOS never moved. The DCU engine now sets $script:DCUNoApplicable when /scan reports 500, and Install-BIOSDCU explicitly falls back to Invoke-DellBIOSFlash on that signal - Flash64W''s DUP framework re-evaluates against the live device directly and is the trusted reference path the legacy BIOS deployments have always used. DriverUpdates semantics are unchanged (a 500 there genuinely is "everything current" across a 30-DUP package). Re-sync to restage the apply script. 2.13.3 extends the same fallback to DCU /applyUpdates returning 500. Field firing on a 5.6.0.17 device with BIOS 1.8.1 vs target 1.9.0: /scan succeeded with the scan gate passing one applicable BIOS update from the catalog, but /applyUpdates'' own internal re-scan declined and returned 500 ("everything current") - typical when the Dell DUP framework''s runtime conditions (AC power, battery level, pending reboot, TPM / Secure Boot state) aren''t met. The engine''s apply path now also sets $script:DCUNoApplicable on the 500 outcome, and Install-BIOSDCU falls back to Flash64W on either signal. DriverUpdates semantics are unchanged (a DUP-loop runtime check is the legacy BIOS path''s job, not the multi-driver path''s). 2.13.4 quiets two benign log noises that show up in the apply log AFTER a successful DCU run that signaled reboot-required (the normal happy-path BIOS apply). dcu-cli refuses every follow-on /configure with exit 5 ("a previous operation requires a system reboot to complete") until the device reboots, so the persistent-catalog re-point and the post-run DAT-managed re-assertion were both logging alarmingly: "Could not point resident DCU at the persistent catalog ... dell.com may remain enabled" and "DCU locked to DAT-managed mode [post-run]: applied ; not supported: scheduleManual(exit 5), scheduleAction(exit 5), ..." - which read like the run partially failed when in reality the BIOS flashed cleanly, the pre-run lockdown is still in effect, and the next engine run after reboot picks up where this one left off. Both branches now detect the "pending reboot from this run" state and log a single calm "deferred until reboot completes" line at Severity 1 instead. No behavior change to the BIOS flash itself; this is just diagnostic noise reduction. 2.13.5 fixes the Deploy Applications tab''s BIOS checkbox missing the new BIOS Updates (DCU) applications: the 2.13.0 Find-DATExistingApplications filter for Type=''BIOS'' was scoped to "BIOS Update - ..." (legacy Flash64W) and explicitly EXCLUDED "BIOS Update (DCU) - ..." so the two sync types could coexist in lookups without collision, which was the right call - but the deploy tab passes Type=''BIOS'' alone, so DCU BIOS apps never appeared in the picker. The checkbox now also requests Type=''BIOSDCU'' so both delivery flavors surface as one user-facing BIOS bucket (the engine choice was made at sync time; at deploy time the admin thinks of these as one category). 2.14.0 begins unifying driver delivery into a single apply script so one Invoke-DATApply.ps1 covers both the full-OS (Application / Intune / maintenance-window) path and OSD task sequences. The script gains an offline mode: when it runs in WinPE (auto-detected via the X: system drive or the MiniNT marker key, or forced with -Offline), Driver mode now injects the pack''s INFs into the OFFLINE image with dism.exe /Add-Driver against the target volume (-TargetPath, else the OSDTargetSystemDrive task-sequence variable, else an auto-detected fixed volume that carries \Windows) instead of pnputil into the running OS. Firmware-class INFs (ClassGuid f2e7dd72-6468-4e36-b6f1-6488f42c1b52 - Surface UEFI/SAM/ME and any OEM firmware) are skipped offline because firmware only installs in the full OS; a fast /Add-Driver /Recurse pass is used when nothing is filtered, otherwise a per-INF pass with a lenient "some-succeeded = success" policy mirroring the online pnputil path. BIOS, BIOSDCU and DriverUpdates modes are skipped with a clear note in WinPE (they require the running OS), and the detection marker / 3010 reboot signal are not used offline (the task sequence owns reboots). The full-OS behavior is unchanged and gated behind the WinPE/-Offline detection. This is the foundation for retiring the legacy Invoke-CMApplyDriverPackage.ps1; dynamic device-identity matching and package download from the ConfigMgr AdminService land in a follow-up build. 2.15.0 completes that unification and replaces the legacy Invoke-CMApplyDriverPackage.ps1 for OSD: a new -DiscoverFromAdminService switch makes the offline path self-driving. In WinPE the apply script now identifies the device (manufacturer, model, SystemSKU via root\wmi MS_SystemInformation, and the Lenovo 4-char machine type), queries the ConfigMgr AdminService (SMS_Package + SMS_DriverPackage over HTTPS, with a dedicated read-only service account or default credentials and an optional self-signed-cert bypass), selects the best driver package by matching the device SystemSKU / machine type / model against each package''s existing "(Models included:...)" description and DAT name conventions - gated by the target OS / architecture and resolved to the newest version - then downloads that package with the task sequence''s OSDDownloadContent agent and injects it via the 2.14.0 offline path. Server and credentials come from -AdminServiceServer / -AdminServiceUser / -AdminServicePassword or the TS variables DATAdminServiceServer / DATAdminServiceUser / DATAdminServicePassword, and the resolved PackageID is also written to DATDriverPackageID so a native "Download Package Content" step can be used instead. Matching reuses the metadata the sync already writes, so no package rebuild is needed. One TS step now services every model; the AdminService matching and content download require validation in a real OSD environment (they cannot be exercised in CI). 2.16.0 fixes Surface driver packages building with the wrong "(Models included:...)" SKU. Surface has no catalog SystemSKU, so Get-SurfaceDriverPack returned no SystemID and the package description fell back to the MODEL NAME (e.g. "Surface Pro 12th Edition Intel") - which never matches a device''s real SystemSKU, so neither the legacy Invoke-CMApplyDriverPackage.ps1 nor the new AdminService matcher could ever bind a Surface package to a device. OEMSources.json Surface entries gain an optional "sku" field (a string, or an array for consumer/commercial/region variants), populated from Microsoft''s Surface System SKU reference for the 2025 devices and other current models (e.g. Surface Pro 12th Edition Intel = Surface_Pro_for_Business_13in_12th_Ed_Intel_2103 + the Korea _2134 variant). Get-SurfaceDriverPack now returns those as SystemID so the description carries the real, semicolon-joined SystemSKU(s); models still missing a "sku" log a Severity-2 warning and fall back to the model name as before. Adding the SystemSKU is documented in CLAUDE.md. Models without a known SKU yet (e.g. the Surface Laptop family, older Pro/Go) still need one added to deploy via OSD matching.'
